{
  "id": "phekb-hepatitis-c-comprehensive",
  "source": "phekb",
  "source_id": "hepatitis-c",
  "name": "Hepatitis C - Comprehensive Provider Query",
  "description": "Simulates a hepatology or infectious disease provider identifying their complete HCV patient population for a treatment cascade or screening initiative. CDC and USPSTF recommend universal HCV screening in adults aged 18-79. Real-world identification primarily unions: HCV diagnosis codes, DAA prescriptions, HCV antibody labs, and HCV RNA viral loads. Like MS, DAA specificity means union is reliable \u2014 minimal cross-indication noise.",
  "prompt": "I need to identify my complete hepatitis C patient population for a screening and treatment cascade quality initiative. From clinical experience, HCV patients are documented in different ways: most have a formal HCV diagnosis (acute or chronic), most have positive HCV antibody screening, many have detectable HCV RNA viral loads, and patients in active treatment are on direct-acting antivirals.\n\nPlease run multiple FHIR queries to capture the full population:\n1. Patients with any HCV diagnosis (parent viral hepatitis C, acute, or chronic)\n2. Patients prescribed direct-acting antivirals (sofosbuvir, ledipasvir, simeprevir, or ribavirin)\n3. Patients with HCV antibody lab results (any value \u2014 positive antibody indicates past or present infection)\n\nFor each query, return the matching resources. I want the union of all patients found across these three approaches.",
  "metadata": {
    "implementation_guide": "US Core 5.0.0",
    "multi_query": true,
    "algorithm_path": "comprehensive",
    "algorithm_path_description": "Union of HCV dx codes, DAA Rx, and HCV antibody labs. Tests provider-level identification for screening/treatment cascade. The DAA query has minimal Path C overcount \u2014 like MS DMTs, DAAs are HCV-specific.",
